1. Connect the iDRAC Port

Every Dell PowerEdge has a dedicated out-of-band management port labeled:

iDRAC

or has “wrench” icon

Steps:

Plug an Ethernet cable into the dedicated iDRAC port.

Connect it to a management switch or any network with DHCP.

Power on the server (even if the OS is not installed, iDRAC boots independently).

2. Access the iDRAC Configuration Menu (BIOS Level)

During boot:

When you see the Dell logo, press
F2 → System Setup
OR
Ctrl + E → iDRAC Settings

Navigate to:
iDRAC Settings → Network

Here you can configure:

Enable NIC → Enabled

NIC Selection → Dedicated

IPv4 Settings

DHCP: On (or Off if using static)

IP Address

Subnet Mask

Gateway

Example Static Config:

IPv4: Enabled
DHCP: Disabled
IP: 192.168.1.50
Mask: 255.255.255.0
GW: 192.168.1.1


Press Apply, then Finish, and reboot if required.

3. Get the Default iDRAC Credentials

The default login depends on generation:

iDRAC8 (R730xd, older models)

User: root

Password: printed on white sticker on pull-out info tag under “iDRAC Password”.

iDRAC9 (R740xd and higher)

User: root

Password: printed on the service tag pull-out card under “iDRAC Password”.

4. Log In to the iDRAC Web Interface

Once network is configured:

Open a browser and enter the iDRAC IP:

https://192.168.1.50


Accept any certificate warnings.

Log in using:

Username: root

Password: (as printed on the server tag)

You should now see the iDRAC dashboard.

5. Change the Default Password (Highly Recommended)

Go to:

iDRAC Settings → User Authentication → Local Users → root → Edit

Set:

New password

Optional: disable unused accounts

6. Optional — Set Up iDRAC Networking Features
DNS Naming

iDRAC Settings → Network → Common Settings

iDRAC Name: servername-idrac

Register with DNS: Yes (optional)

Enable/Disable VLAN

If using management VLAN:

Enable VLAN: ON
VLAN ID: <your VLAN>
Priority: 1

7. Optional — Set Up Email Alerts

Go to:

iDRAC Settings → Alerts → SMTP

Configure:

SMTP Server

From Address

Recipients

Test email

8. Optional — Update iDRAC Firmware

Download firmware from Dell:
Search “iDRAC firmware R730xd” or “iDRAC9 firmware R740xd”

Upload via:
Maintenance → System Update

Keeps features and security patches current.

9. Optional — Assign a Static IP via RACADM CLI (Advanced)

If you cannot access BIOS:

Login via SSH or console:

racadm setniccfg -s 192.168.1.50 255.255.255.0 192.168.1.1


Reboot iDRAC:

racadm racreset

10. Confirm iDRAC is Working

From a workstation:

ping 192.168.1.50


Open browser to that IP and verify:

System information is loading

Sensors are reporting correctly

You can open Virtual Console

You can mount ISOs